00:13:24.160 --> 00:13:27.830
You guys had some excellent
and quite tricky questions.

00:13:27.830 --> 00:13:31.030
Luca$sino asks what we would
really see if we followed

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:33.770
the monkey directly
through the event horizon?

00:13:33.770 --> 00:13:37.060
Would it appear ahead of us
despite previously appearing

00:13:37.060 --> 00:13:39.460
frozen on the event horizon?

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:41.710
Well, sort of, yes.

00:13:41.710 --> 00:13:44.470
The light from the instant
of the monkey's crossing

00:13:44.470 --> 00:13:47.260
of the event horizon
is eternally trapped

00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:48.790
at that horizon.

00:13:48.790 --> 00:13:52.480
It's trying to walk upwards
on a downward escalator

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:54.340
of spacetime.

00:13:54.340 --> 00:13:57.670
But you're traveling
down that same escalator

00:13:57.670 --> 00:14:00.010
and so you pass this light.

00:14:00.010 --> 00:14:03.220
And so you see the instant
of the monkey's crossing.

00:14:03.220 --> 00:14:05.710
The escalator speeds
up as you descend.

00:14:05.710 --> 00:14:09.210
And so light that the monkey
emitted from below that point

00:14:09.210 --> 00:14:13.330
is trying to go up, but is
actually going downwards.

00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:16.210
And yet, you're traveling
downwards faster.

00:14:16.210 --> 00:14:18.760
So you overtake
some of that light,

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:21.540
which means you see the
monkey ahead of you.

00:14:21.540 --> 00:14:23.350
Douglas Oak asks
a great question

00:14:23.350 --> 00:14:25.210
that I've heard asked before.

00:14:25.210 --> 00:14:27.670
If time dilation
approaches infinity,

00:14:27.670 --> 00:14:30.250
do you reach the singularity
before the black hole

00:14:30.250 --> 00:14:31.850
evaporates?

00:14:31.850 --> 00:14:32.350
OK.

00:14:32.350 --> 00:14:36.610
So a distant immortal observer,
with a ridiculously good

00:14:36.610 --> 00:14:39.550
telescope, will detect
photons from the falling

00:14:39.550 --> 00:14:42.580
monkey at all future times.

00:14:42.580 --> 00:14:45.760
Eventually, those photons will
come billions, even trillions,

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:49.720
of years apart from each other
and be hugely redshifted.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:55.180
For an eternal non-leaking black
hole, there is no last photon.

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:57.290
But real black holes decay.

00:14:57.290 --> 00:14:59.590
And so the final burst
of Hawking radiation

00:14:59.590 --> 00:15:02.620
as a black hole evaporates
will be accompanied

00:15:02.620 --> 00:15:05.260
by all of the
remaining light emitted

00:15:05.260 --> 00:15:08.200
by everything that fell into
it as it crossed the event

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:09.750
horizon.

00:15:09.750 --> 00:15:12.670
But the infalling
stuff isn't saved.

00:15:12.670 --> 00:15:15.520
Although we never saw the
moment of its crossing,

00:15:15.520 --> 00:15:16.910
that did happen.

00:15:16.910 --> 00:15:20.590
Its matter became part of
the black hole and re-emerges

00:15:20.590 --> 00:15:22.960
as that Hawking radiation.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:26.020
Grim Reaper Of Trolls is
curious about taking their warp

00:15:26.020 --> 00:15:27.800
drive into a black hole.

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:29.530
Well, I would encourage it.

00:15:29.530 --> 00:15:31.510
You can escape a black
hole by traveling faster

00:15:31.510 --> 00:15:32.860
than the speed of light.

00:15:32.860 --> 00:15:35.440
In principle, you can do
that with a warp drive.

00:15:35.440 --> 00:15:38.290
The probably impossible
technology of the warp drive

00:15:38.290 --> 00:15:40.510
allows you to cause
a patch of space

00:15:40.510 --> 00:15:44.530
to move at really any speed
you have the energy to reach.

00:15:44.530 --> 00:15:47.800
So you could resist the
faster-than-light flow of space

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:49.480
within the black hole.

00:15:49.480 --> 00:15:51.670
The event horizon
itself just wouldn't

00:15:51.670 --> 00:15:54.430
apply within your warp bubble.

00:15:54.430 --> 00:15:57.550
You know, there's probably
a Penrose diagram for this.

00:15:57.550 --> 00:15:59.500
I'll look into it.

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:02.259
Some people complained about
my use of the expression

00:16:02.259 --> 00:16:04.300
"escape velocity greater
than the speed of light"

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:06.050
at the beginning of the episode.

00:16:06.050 --> 00:16:08.110
First, let me note that
I gave that statement

00:16:08.110 --> 00:16:12.010
in a list of popular examples
of oversimplifications

00:16:12.010 --> 00:16:13.750
about black holes.

00:16:13.750 --> 00:16:17.470
Second, it's not actually
an incorrect statement.

00:16:17.470 --> 00:16:21.080
Despite the derision it
receives in nerd circles,

00:16:21.080 --> 00:16:22.990
it's accepted to
talk about the escape

00:16:22.990 --> 00:16:25.240
velocity at the
surface of the Earth

00:16:25.240 --> 00:16:28.890
because we're used to
Newtonian approximations there.

00:16:28.890 --> 00:16:31.630
But it's no less accurate
near a black hole.

00:16:31.630 --> 00:16:34.420
At the event horizon, you need
to travel at the speed of light

00:16:34.420 --> 00:16:36.640
relative to the black
hole's stationary frame

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:39.970
of reference as recorded
by a distant observer.

00:16:39.970 --> 00:16:43.330
That's the velocity
you need to escape.

00:16:43.330 --> 00:16:45.640
The reason that people
poo-poo the expression "escape

00:16:45.640 --> 00:16:49.810
velocity" is that it reminds
us of a strange coincidence.

00:16:49.810 --> 00:16:52.090
You happen to get exactly
the right size for the event

00:16:52.090 --> 00:16:55.870
horizon if you use Newtonian
gravity to calculate

00:16:55.870 --> 00:16:58.210
the distance at which the
escape velocity reaches

00:16:58.210 --> 00:16:59.614
the speed of light.

00:16:59.614 --> 00:17:01.030
The correct way
to get this number

00:17:01.030 --> 00:17:03.850
is by using general relativity
to find the point where

00:17:03.850 --> 00:17:06.500
the flow of spacetime
reaches the speed of light.

00:17:06.500 --> 00:17:10.300
But the concept of escape
velocity at the event horizon

00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:14.200
is still as meaningful as it is
from the surface of the Earth.

00:17:14.200 --> 00:17:18.520
It's a useful classical
simplification in both cases.

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:20.210
Cornerrecord asks
about that thing when

00:17:20.210 --> 00:17:21.950
you're in a black
hole and time becomes

00:17:21.950 --> 00:17:24.260
space and space becomes time?

00:17:24.260 --> 00:17:26.720
Well, that's probably a
topic for an entire video.

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:29.960
So for now, I'll just
quote what's his name.

00:17:29.960 --> 00:17:33.740
The inward direction acts
like the future direction.

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:36.890
So once inside the horizon,
avoiding a singularity

00:17:36.890 --> 00:17:38.900
is like avoiding next Tuesday.

